Issue 2 — recreating the menu every time

Yes, setItems does popById("battle.actionmenu") then push<ActionMenuWindow>(...) on every call, and clear() pops it — so the window object is destroyed and reallocated each time the menu opens or its items change. BattleHud.cpp:25-28 BattleHud.cpp:51-56

Why it's structured that way: UIManager only renders and routes input to windows currently on m_stack. Push = show, pop = hide. There's no "hidden but alive" state, so open/close is expressed as create/destroy. UIManager.h:18-43

Honest assessment: this is not a per-frame cost — it only happens on menu open/close or item change (user actions), and ActionMenuWindow is a tiny object (two vectors + ints), so it's not a performance problem. It's a design smell, not a bug.

If you want it created once, the change is:

    Add a visible/enabled flag to UIWindow, and have UIManager::handleInput/render skip windows where it's false (instead of relying on presence in the stack).
    In BattleHud, create the ActionMenuWindow once (constructor or lazily) and store the pointer as a member.
    Replace push/popById with setVisible(true)/setVisible(false) + setItems(...) on the stored pointer.

That's a UIWindow/UIManager change, not just a BattleHud one, because the show/hide model currently lives in the manager's stack. Given the cost is negligible, I'd only do it if you're standardizing show/hide across all windows — otherwise the rename in Issue 1 is the higher-value fix.

One caveat if you do make it persistent: ActionMenuWindow::setItems resets m_selected/m_scroll to the first enabled item every call, so keeping the object alive won't preserve cursor position unless you also stop resetting those. ActionMenuWindow.cpp:41-55

